\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Family background}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Born }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid3363200 ****}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 
 Malta, during siege. Parents had met in Berlin, where mother au pair to leading Jewish families. Both went on to Malta, after they married.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Father Oxford graduate in German and French, teaching English in Berlin. Head of supplies in Malta. Bombing and hunger. JO\rquote 
s second name Melita after the island; brought up with hybrid identity. Has revisited and lectured there.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 When mother pregnant with second child evacuated to Egypt, sent on to Cape Town where child (Elaine) born, living with white Afrika
ans family. Father run over by lorry, on crutches, came to Durban. Family sent with other British women by boat in convoy to Liverpool. Ships before and after them torpedoed, hundreds of women and children drowned. Band to greet them. These are indirect m
emories, family stories. First direct memory is arriving in Bristol station, greeted by grandmother with teddy bear.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Mother\rquote s family upper bourgeois, rented beautiful house by Martock church, Somerset. Grandmother one of 17 children, parents died when she 
was a child. Stocker family, owned kaolin mines in Cornwall and china factory in Midlands. Arranged marriage at 18 to `strange man\rquote 
, Branston Bradford, his family corn and coal merchants. She was fine operatic singer but he forbad her to sing. Then disappeared into alcoholism. Later came to live in part of Judith\rquote 
s widowed mother and sang again. Bourgeois women not allowed to develop their talents.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Paternal grandmother also very gifted. Great-great-grandfather J. Beecham, artist and great grandfather Kenne
th J. Beecham historian of Cirencester. Grandmother took to her bed, lay in back room of their Wimbledon house. Grandfather, civil servant, waited on her. Great reader but unable to go to university. Grandfather did send JO\rquote 
s father to Dulwich College [after winning scholarship]. Mother considered downwardly mobile in marrying father because he had insufficient property \endash  his Oxford education disregarded.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Never met grandfather Bradford, corn merchant, who was a friend of Thomas Hardy. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Father\rquote s sister also brilliant and unrealised, worshipped father. Father\rquote s brother jealous, became alcoholic.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Father died of polio when JO 9. Taught a year in school at East Grinstead, then a year at RAF Cranwell College, Lincs. He read French books to her as she sat on his
 knee, translating spontaneously. Cycling together. Last memory waving goodbye to him as they went on holiday in July expecting to see him in three days. Mother did not tell them he had polio [and in an iron lung for three months], said he had flu. Only S
eptember grandmother said father had been ill and was now \lquote happy\rquote , and they were to go to boarding school. Then in school told by other girls that father had died, and finally by mother on school visit.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Told by matron not to cry. Felt \lquote I hate this culture\rquote 
, you cannot grieve: this led towards anthropology. Her later discussion of death rituals among Gypsies, and how Gypsy children not separated from knowledge of death. Photos of Gypsy children at funerals. [JO witnessed such funerals alongside the grieving
 children.] Lady Diana\rquote s death.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Father had wanted her to go to grammar school and Oxford. But RAF paid for boarding school, where ideally aimed to become debutantes [or at least make upper class marriages].}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Mother later took part-time social admin/sociology degree at LSE. Had been volunteer in Citizen\rquote 
s Advice Bureau, and WVS. After widowed got deposit on house, worked for old people\rquote s welfare in Hammersmith. Evening classes taught by a white Russian called Mr. Skidelsky, (not Robert Skidelsky, but an olde
r postgraduate) `the ultimate intellectual\rquote 
, prepared JO for Oxford entrance, also coached mother for A levels. She graduated 1958. Worked in as social worker in Stevenage, then taught at Battersea Poly, ended as lecturer at Surrey University. Did talk together a lot, but mother couldn\rquote 
t understand about the school, had had a governess. Hooked on ethnography, introduced JO to Marsden and Jackson [and Townsend].}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 At 15 JO insisted must leave the school. Godmother Kate Nicholson also a frustrated woman. JO reading under blanket at night. Took entrance to St Paul\rquote s, didn\rquote 
t pass but offered place because she had O levels already, turned it down because headmistress said it would prevent mother\rquote s evening work. Later wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 New Society}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  article on \lquote Girls and their bodies\rquote  at suggestion of Paul Barker. Only years later explained this to mother.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 French mistress advised JO to go to university. Headmistress against this. By then had 12 O Levels, studying for 4 A Levels.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 
Sister Elaine went to therapist in US for problems [in the 1980s], only then came to realise that their childhood had been abnormal. Very talented. Advised by science teacher to go to university. Later told JO, \lquote You saved me\rquote 
, by persuading mother to let her leave the school and go to Ealing Tech. Went to Trinity College, Dublin, First. Ph D at Imperial College on insects on cowpats. But always tormented because school had told her she was no good.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Married, went to Brazil, husband worked for World Bank. Ha
d children, he left her in relative poverty, but they have done well. Now in Exeter with new partner. Helps Judith with garden. Mutual bond. Mother at end of her life regretted sending them to boarding school. Mother\rquote 
s will. Contents of house, difficulty of sharing. As a child, Judith comforted Elaine in dormitory, so became a mother at 9. Elaine insisted her children went to day school, gave them compensatory love.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Became close to mother at end of life. In 1976 mother retired, Elaine married, JO got first
 lectureship at Durham: which was traumatic experience of sexism. Library refused to give her a card, similarly blocked from eating in staff common room, assumed was a student.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Mother liked qualitative research, but not well regarded by other staff, so ad
vised students not to work with her. Wept at this. Judith shared understanding. Too heavy teaching load to write a doctorate. Support also from union and loyal students, but took early retirement. From childhood encouraged JO to get professional training,
 you can\rquote t depend on marriage. Suggested go to secretarial college, but contemporary had been to Sorbonne, and mother took up this idea. \'a320 term fees paid from grandmother\rquote s shares.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 So although failed French A Level went to Sorbonne to study French civilisation. Could read what she wanted, \lquote wandered free\rquote  in streets. Lecturers \lquote 
superstars\rquote . Decided she wanted to go to Oxford. Mother found could get full grant from LEA. Tutored for entrance by Skidelsky.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Mother \lquote had to fight to get employment\rquote ; \lquote rampant feminism\rquote . Gave her J.S. Mill }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 The Subjection of Women}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  the night before JO went to Paris. Skidelsky radicalised them. He, JO and mother all opposed Suez Canal war.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Geography of childhood: by boat to Liverpool; then East Grinstead, living in grandparents\rquote  hou
se, while father taught in grammar school; then to Cranwell College, Lincs, living in tiny cottage near Ruskington. After father\rquote s death (1950), children to boarding school, mother to London for Hammersmith job, buying a house in Acton/Ealing.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 School education}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 First school primary in East Grinstead and then in Ruskington. One teacher reported Judith \lquote brilliant\rquote 
. Developed northern accents. Taught looped writing style, which boarding school said was maids\rquote  writing. Had to relearn this and also accent.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid8534382 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Upper Chine School}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  [1950-59], boarding school on Isle of Wight, a \lquote prison\rquote 
. On recent visit found it closed, got it filmed; since bulldozed. School had elite students from Iran, Singapore, Canada etc. Learnt Persian from fellow student. Mimi Khalvati, pupil, has written poetry book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 The Chine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 
; JO has recorded interview with her. JO hated it from early on. Not allowed to cry, to grieve the loss of the most important person in her life. Had to retreat into her imagination. Hated the rules. Miss Passmore who stuck [index finger] into her back, 
\lquote stand up straight\rquote . No arms on table. Emphasis on sport, but JO not sporty. Bodily control, hence relevance later of Foucault. Every book you wanted had to be approved by headmistress. No talking in passages, or after light
s out. Electric bells rang every 20 minutes. Given 3 minutes to get up. \lquote Orders, orders, discipline, discipline\rquote .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Susan Caffery, later sociology lecturer, said that JO and she became intellectuals because they didn\rquote t fit in \endash  not part of a normal nuclear 
family. School unable to handle pupils\rquote  crises. Friend Jenny went mad after grandfather died, school unable to recognise this. When JO broke her arm, told she was seeking attention because father had died. Elaine not attended to when broke foot.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 For JO most positively encouraging was French teacher. Aubrey de Selincourt (whose daughter married Christopher Robin), translator of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Iliad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 , retired intellectual, also inspiring. A Levels in English Lang and Lit. But school didn\rquote 
t expect girls to go to university. School \lquote a preparation for dependence\rquote , to make a good marriage. Best friend Sue left at 16, very bitter. Elaine gave up career for husband and boys.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Drawing on your own memories is unusual, but her }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Anthropology and Autobiography}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  is now called \lquote classic\rquote . Recent article, \lquote Written out and written in\rquote . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Oxford, St Hilda\rquote s [1961-65]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Did poorly in PPE finals, no good at unseen exams. Politics don Sybil Crowe, whose father Sir Eyre Crowe wrote the Zinoviev letter, very
 right wing, asked for essays not related to the course. Course poor, but fellow students outstanding: e.g. Bob Rowthorne, Sheila Rowbotham, Gareth Stedman Jones (at first boyfriend), Angus Hone, all on left. Amazing discussions, reading Marcuse and other
 books not on syllabus. Awarded 3rd, feels \lquote injustice\rquote , examiners sniggering at her at the viva.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
