\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Sorbonne [1959-61]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 While at Sorbonne briefly lodged with family but fo
und sharing with two English girls, so moved to Cercle Concordia, joining ex-schoolmate Mariam (Iranian), international hostel, with room of her own. For first time \lquote I could celebrate being an intellectual\rquote 
. [At boarding school had] read Colin Wilson }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 The Outsider}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  \endash  \lquote That was what I was
\rquote ; through his influence read Camus, Tolstoy, Dostoevsky, T.E. Lawrence. \lquote I read from dawn to dusk\rquote . Kept sexually restrained, influence by Mariam who believed in one love for life. Parisians not open or welcoming. Visiting ar
t galleries, cinemas. \lquote It was just a cultural paradise\rquote . Returned to London to revise for Oxford entrance with Skidelsky, then back to Sorbonne. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Courses based on French baccalaur\'e9at. French politics (Maurice Duverger), literature, geography, history, lan
guage. Read Balzac, Verlaine, Baudelaire, etc. Skiing holiday, met friend Hubert, drove to Mediterranean in a group. Met English girl in hostel, Margaret, (who was about to go to Cambridge) hitched around France together: she married (now Professor) John 
Parry, still friends.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Oxford St Hilda\rquote s [1961-65]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Studying French and Latin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  Difficulty of getting admitted after failing re-sit of Latin
 entrance exam. Latin proved a nightmare. Failed Prelims, but left-wing tutor, Gerry Fowler] later MP, coached her, and she passed re-sit. Then because of bad teaching in French, based on writing in English, decided to switch to PPE. [Hence four years at 
Oxford, funded by LEA.]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 
Became socialist and atheist in France. Opposed Suez war and policies in Cyprus. At start in Paris, had attended Anglican church, but soon lost belief. Mariam also an influence. Demonstrations for Algerian freedom. Reading }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Le canard enchain\'e9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 The Second Sex. 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 
At Oxford started reading socialist texts including Marx. Joined Labour Club and CND in first  term, met Bob Rowthorne  then Gareth Stedman Jones in second year. Even before Oxford JO was thinking she wanted to see women in th
e Union. Women only allowed in balcony and could not speak. Befriended Roderick Floud, formed a committee, supported by Michael Beloff and Jonathan Aitken, toured colleges canvassing. First attempt lost. John Sparrow bussed in life members. A term later, 
the vote won. JO put her name down as first woman member, worldwide press coverage \endash  but did not speak for some time.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 Significant tutors? None in French. In PPE, right-wing Miss Crowe. Notable lecturers Alastair Macintyre and A.L. Hart, although not about 
the syllabus. Through Gareth chose political theory with Steven Lukes and social theory with Brian Wilson. Steven \lquote threw me a landline\rquote , saying she had written the best essay he had heard on Marx: \lquote Steven gave me hope\rquote 
. Wanted to do MA, which Miss Crowe opposed, but Steven backed JO. Many women tutors bitter and unadventurous.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382\charrsid8534382 
Mad social life, one woman for every nine men, wild time. Thought had met the love of her life, who went to prison for a demonstration, but turned out to be a serial seducer. Depress
ed. Gave up the idea of life-long love. Had many lovers, then a good time with Gareth, and after him with Hugh. At student later re-union, many said JO an inspiration. Girls found in bed with boyfriend expelled: college like a boarding school. Judith 
\lquote figurehead\rquote  of resistance.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid8534382 
